e (film)|Yardie]]'' || August 24, 2018 || Distributed by [[StudioCanal UK]]\n|-\n| ''[[Johnny English Strikes Again]]'' || October 12, 2018 || Distributed by Universal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Cold Pursuit]]'' || February 8, 2019 || Distributed by [[Summit Entertainment]]\n|-\n|''[[A Shaun the Sheep Movie: Farmageddon]]''|| 18 October 2019 ||  Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Aardman Animations]] \n|}\n\n===2020s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Release date\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Chicken Run 2]]'' || TBA ||  Distributed by [[Lionsgate|Lions Gate Entertainment]]<br />Production company [[Path\u00e9]] and [[Aardman Animations]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.studiocanal.com/}}\n*[http://www.studiocanal.com/en/studiocanal-group/historical Official history]\n\n{{Vivendi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Studiocanal}}\n[[Category:Canal+ Group]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of France]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of France]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Vivendi subsidiaries]]\n", "name_user": "Skywatcher68", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected filmography:verified more production credits. Still work to be done.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/StudioCanal"}
{"title_page": "Eve Watkinson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Irish stage, film and television actress.}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Eve Watkinson\n| image       =Eve_Watkinson.jpg\n\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 6 March 1909\n| birth_place = [[Terenure]]\n| death_date  = 15 November 1999\n| death_place = [[Monkstown, County Dublin]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =Actress\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = Irish\n}}\n'''Eve Watkinson''' (6 March 1909 \u2013 15 November 1999) was an Irish stage, film and television actress.\n==Biography==\nEve Panton Watkinson was born 6 March 1909 in [[Terenure]] to Arthur Panton Watkinson and Kate n\u00e9e Hollingsworth.<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |title=house 1 in Healthfield Road (Terenure, Dublin) |url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Dublin/Terenure/Healthfield_Road/42038/ |website=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Birth record\">{{cite web |title=Birth record search |url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1909/01614/1647294.pdf |website=Irish genealogy - Civil Records |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her father was the director of an interior decorating company called A. Panton Watkinson on St Stephen's Green. She learned acting working with an amateur group in [[Capel Street]] called [[Torch Theatre, Dublin|Torch Theatre]]. She went on to work with [[Edward Pakenham, 6th Earl of Longford|Edward]] and [[Christine Longford]]'s company based in the [[Gate Theatre]]. Watkinson performed in leading roles in plays by Ibsen, Sheridan, Coleman, Shakespeare and Fry. She played the Vampire Monster Mallarka in ''[[Carmilla]]'' and gained that became her nickname with the company. Left an inheritance enough to live on, Watkinson used the money she earned in acting to produce productions of her own.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\">{{cite web | title=Monster Mallarka of Dublin theatre | website=The Irish Times | date=7 April 2020 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/monster-mallarka-of-dublin-theatre-1.254881 | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWatkinson also spent several years with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] Theatre company.<ref name=\"Wearing 2014 p. 442\">{{cite book | last=Wearing | first=J.P. | title=The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers | series=The London Stage | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-8108-9308-5 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=5g2PBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA442 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=442}}</ref> When [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] began to produce television plays, she had several roles including in plays by Durrenmatt, [[Christopher Nolan (author)|Christopher Nolan]] and Frank O'Connor. She went with Torchlight and Laser Beams to the Edinburgh Festival. She also worked as a presenter for RTE Radio. <ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web |title=RT\u00c9 Radio Scripts |url=https://www.ucd.ie/archives/t4media/p0260-rte-radio-talk%20-scripts-in-english-descriptive-catalogue.pdf |publisher=UCD |page=12 ||access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In the 1960s Watkinson narrated stories for children.<ref name=\"Billboard p. 23\">{{cite magazine | title=Special Merit Albums |work=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=ARgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT23 | date=24 November 1962 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=23}}</ref>  Watkinson had a role in the 1988 Irish film ''[[Reefer and the Model]]''. Watkinson died in [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\"/><ref name=\"Dobson 2010 p. 308\">{{cite book | last=Dobson | first=N. | title=The A to Z of Animation and Cartoons | publisher=Scarecrow Press | series=A to Z guides | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8108-7623-1 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=dJRa_8AJkkUC&pg=PA308 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=308}}</ref>\n\n==Excerpt Playography==\n* ''Hedda Gabler''\n* ''Rosmersholm''\n* ''The Lady from the Sea''\n* ''The Dark is Light Enough''\n* ''The School for Scandal''\n* ''The Jealous Wife''\n* ''The Physicists''\n* ''The Moment next to nothing''\n* ''Torchlight and Laser Beams''\n* ''The Moses Rock''\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watkinson, Eve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish television actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Irish stage, film and television actress.}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Eve Watkinson\n| image       =Eve_Watkinson.jpg\n\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 6 March 1909\n| birth_place = [[Terenure]]\n| death_date  = 15 November 1999\n| death_place = [[Monkstown, County Dublin]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =Actress\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = Irish\n}}\n'''Eve Watkinson''' (6 March 1909 \u2013 15 November 1999) was an Irish stage, film and television actress.\n==Biography==\nEve Panton Watkinson was born 6 March 1909 in [[Terenure]] to Arthur Panton Watkinson and Kate n\u00e9e Hollingsworth.<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |title=house 1 in Healthfield Road (Terenure, Dublin) |url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Dublin/Terenure/Healthfield_Road/42038/ |website=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Birth record\">{{cite web |title=Birth record search |url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1909/01614/1647294.pdf |website=Irish genealogy - Civil Records |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her father was the director of an interior decorating company called A. Panton Watkinson on St Stephen's Green. She learned acting working with an amateur group in [[Capel Street]] called [[Torch Theatre, Dublin|Torch Theatre]]. She went on to work with [[Edward Pakenham, 6th Earl of Longford|Edward]] and [[Christine Longford]]'s company based in the [[Gate Theatre]]. Watkinson performed in leading roles in plays by Ibsen, Sheridan, Coleman, Shakespeare and Fry. She played the Vampire Monster Mallarka in ''[[Carmilla]]'' and gained that became her nickname with the company. Left an inheritance enough to live on, Watkinson used the money she earned in acting to produce productions of her own.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\">{{cite web | title=Monster Mallarka of Dublin theatre | website=The Irish Times | date=7 April 2020 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/monster-mallarka-of-dublin-theatre-1.254881 | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWatkinson also spent several years with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] Theatre company.<ref name=\"Wearing 2014 p. 442\">{{cite book | last=Wearing | first=J.P. | title=The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers | series=The London Stage | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-8108-9308-5 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=5g2PBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA442 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=442}}</ref> When [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] began to produce television plays, she had several roles including in plays by Durrenmatt, [[Christopher Nolan (author)|Christopher Nolan]] and Frank O'Connor. She went with Torchlight and Laser Beams to the Edinburgh Festival. She also worked as a presenter for RTE Radio. <ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web |title=RT\u00c9 Radio Scripts |url=https://www.ucd.ie/archives/t4media/p0260-rte-radio-talk%20-scripts-in-english-descriptive-catalogue.pdf |publisher=UCD |page=12 ||access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In the 1960s Watkinson narrated stories for children.<ref name=\"Billboard p. 23\">{{cite magazine | title=Special Merit Albums |work=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=ARgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT23 | date=24 November 1962 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=23}}</ref>  Watkinson had a role in the 1988 Irish film ''[[Reefer and the Model]]''. Watkinson died in [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\"/><ref name=\"Dobson 2010 p. 308\">{{cite book | last=Dobson | first=N. | title=The A to Z of Animation and Cartoons | publisher=Scarecrow Press | series=A to Z guides | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8108-7623-1 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=dJRa_8AJkkUC&pg=PA308 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=308}}</ref>\n\n==Excerpt Playography==\n* Hedda Gabler \n* Rosmersholm\n* The Lady from the Sea\n* The Dark is Light Enough \n* The School for Scandal\n* The Jealous Wife\n* The Physicists\n* The Moment next to nothing\n* Torchlight and Laser Beams\n* The Moses Rock \n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watkinson, Eve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish television actresses]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExcerpt Playography:italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eve_Watkinson"}
